<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the scoped role
    `x_[scope]_case_viewer` inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    This is the lowest-tier (read-only) operational user role for the
    case-management POC. Per AAP Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix), it grants
    READ-ONLY ACCESS across the three custom tables:
        - x_[scope]_case        (Read All; no Create / no Write / no Delete)
        - x_[scope]_case_task   (Read All; no Create / no Write / no Delete)
        - x_[scope]_case_party  (Read All; no Create / no Write / no Delete)
    Unlike the case_agent role, this role's read scope is NOT restricted to
    "Assigned only" — viewers may read every record in the three custom
    tables regardless of the assigned_agent / assigned_group values.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map), this role has
    NO authority to drive any state transition. Viewers cannot move a case
    from Draft to Open, Open to In Progress, In Progress to Pending,
    Pending to In Progress, In Progress to Resolved, or Resolved to Closed.
    All transition guards in ../flows/sub_flows/ implicitly reject viewer
    callers because the OnUpdate trigger fires only on records the caller
    can write, and viewers have no write privilege.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        ArkCase's `application.roles` list pattern, where role names were
        held as plain strings bound from external configuration via the
        @ListValue("application.roles") annotation. The case_viewer role
        corresponds to ArkCase's lowest-privilege "viewer" tier in that
        list — typically a stakeholder, auditor, or supervisor who needs
        visibility into case operations without authority to modify data.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/model/RolePrivilegesConstants.java
        defines the legacy `ROLE_` prefix (intentionally NOT used in the
        target; replaced by the scope prefix `x_[scope]_`).
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        ArkCase's role-normalization logic (uppercase,
        whitespace-to-underscore, periods-to-double-underscore, prepend
        `ROLE_`). The ServiceNow target replaces this entire mechanism with
        named scoped roles whose privileges are enforced declaratively by
        ACLs in ../acl/.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: the role's `name` is `x_[scope]_case_viewer`
        (literal `[scope]` placeholder preserved per AAP convention), and the
        `sys_scope` / `sys_package` fields bind the role to the scoped
        application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope writes.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `sys_scope` and
        `sys_package` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical role identifier `x_[scope]_case_viewer`) and
        is NOT a reference to any other record.
      - No role inheritance: `<includes_roles/>` is empty/self-closing. This
        role does NOT extend or include any out-of-the-box ServiceNow role
        (e.g., admin, itil, snc_internal, personalize_dictionary,
        report_admin) and does NOT include the sibling scoped roles
        (x_[scope]_case_manager, x_[scope]_case_agent). All read privileges
        flow EXCLUSIVELY from the scoped READ ACLs in ../acl/:
          - ../acl/x_[scope]_case_read_viewer.xml
          - ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_read_viewer.xml
          - ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_read_viewer.xml
        Critical: if `<includes_roles/>` were ever populated with an OOB
        role like `admin`, `itil`, or `snc_internal`, the case_viewer role
        would silently inherit those OOB privileges and break the
        "READ-ONLY" guarantee from the AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL matrix. This
        is enforced by emitting an empty self-closing element here.
      - No PII: the `<description>` is the literal authorization summary
        per the assigned-folder requirements; no real names, email
        addresses, or organization names appear.
      - Standard role (not scoped admin): `<scoped_admin>` is `false`. The
        role does NOT grant administration of the scoped application's
        metadata; scoped-app administration remains the responsibility of
        the OOB `admin` role.
      - Standard privilege level (not elevated): `<elevated_privilege>` is
        `false`. No security elevation beyond what scoped ACLs provide.
      - Not delegable: `<can_delegate>` is `false`. Role grants are managed
        through `sys_user_has_role` records, not via Delegated Admin.
      - Grantable: `<grantable>` is `true`, allowing assignment to users
        through standard role-grant records (e.g., the demo viewer seed in
        ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml).

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3): this role is the
    central piece for "case_viewer cannot write" — the gate's pass
    condition is enforced by the absence of any WRITE / CREATE / DELETE
    ACL referencing this role's `name`. The role record itself enables
    the gate; the absence of write privileges is enforced at the ACL
    layer, not on this record.

    Update Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      - The scope record (../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml and
        ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml) MUST be loaded BEFORE this role
        record (since `sys_scope` and `sys_package` reference the scope by
        source attribute).
      - This role record MUST be loaded BEFORE all ACLs in ../acl/ that
        reference `x_[scope]_case_viewer` by name.
      - This role record MUST be loaded BEFORE seed-data/role_assignments
        that reference `x_[scope]_case_viewer` by name.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user_role">
    <sys_user_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <can_delegate>false</can_delegate>
        <description>Read-only on all x_[scope] case data.</description>
        <elevated_privilege>false</elevated_privilege>
        <grantable>true</grantable>
        <includes_roles/>
        <name>x_[scope]_case_viewer</name>
        <scoped_admin>false</scoped_admin>
        <suffix>case_viewer</suffix>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user_role</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>e3cd650e33c6bfc335732e94683beca1</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_[scope]_case_viewer</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]_case_management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_viewer</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
    </sys_user_role>
</record_update>
